+- kill-arg-redirect-parse: a redirection ("N>word"/"N<word") right
+  after a command argument that's both (a) preceded somewhere earlier
+  by a "-N"-shaped argument (a dash followed only by digits, e.g. a
+  signal number given to the new `kill` builtin -- `kill -0 "$pid"`)
+  and (b) itself quoted or the result of an expansion, is not
+  recognized as a redirection at all -- it's handed to the command as
+  a literal trailing argument instead. A literal (unquoted, unexpanded)
+  word in that same position parses fine, so this isn't about
+  redirection parsing in general, just this specific combination.
+  Found via `kill -0 "$pid" 2>/dev/null` (kill sees "2>/dev/null" as a
+  bogus extra operand); not yet isolated to the exact parser state
+  involved.
+
+    echo -0 "x" 2>/dev/null
+    # prints "-0 x 2>/dev/null" -- should print "-0 x" (to stdout,
+    # with fd 2 redirected to /dev/null)
+
+    echo -0 x 2>/dev/null
+    # prints "-0 x" correctly -- only the quoted/expanded case breaks
+
